article.description: Sheryl Swoopes scored 16 points to lead the Houston Comets to a 75-65 win Saturday over the slumping Charlotte Sting.
article.headline: All-Star Swoopes scores 16
article.linkText: Comets make it four straight, down slumping Sting
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes scored 16 points, helping the Houston Comets extend their season-high winning streak to four games with a 75-65 win Saturday over the slumping Charlotte Sting.

Swoopes, selected a starter for the All-Star Game, had 10 second-half points. She finished 6-of-11 from the field and had five assists.

Dominique Canty had 14 points on 6-of-9 shooting, Janeth Arcain added 12 and Michelle Snow had 11 for Houston (8-5).

Tangela Smith scored 19 points and Alison Feaster added 17, the only players in double figures for the last-place Sting (2-12).

Charlotte starting center Tammy Sutton-Brown had six points in 17 minutes and forward Sheri Sam shot 1-for-8 and also finished with six points. Rookie reserve Janel McCarville had four points and two rebounds in 19 minutes.

"When we came into the game, our plan was to double-down on their post players," Swoopes said. "We had to make some adjustments later in the half and then again in the middle of the second half. There are times in the game that you have to do that in order to get the win."

After losing a season-high four straight, the Comets have won two against San Antonio and one against Seattle, the defending WNBA champions.

The Sting used a 10-2 run to pull to 44-42 on three free throws by Sam. But the Comets, who shot 52 percent from the field, pulled away with a 12-2 run highlighted by a 24-foot 3-pointer by Swoopes.

"Our job is to go out there, stay focused and try to create something offensively," Canty said. "We knew they were going to make a run at us in the second half and they did. We knew it would be important to keep the lead today and keep them from getting too
confident."

Feaster made 5-of-6 3-pointers for Charlotte, which fell to 0-6 on the road and 1-7 all-time in Houston. Feaster's five 3s were a season high.

Houston took a 66-51 lead after Adrienne Goodson's layup with 4:21 left. The Sting pulled to 66-61 with 1:46 left, but the Comets closed out the game with a 9-4 run.

Smith finished 9-of-23 from the field and had eight rebounds in the losing effort.

"We did our best and fought hard, but we just didn't have enough to come back," Smith said. "I know I took a lot of shots and I didn't shoot well, but I was just trying to make something happen for us."

Feaster led Charlotte, which trailed 36-26 at halftime, with nine first-half points on 3-pointers.

The Comets' four-game streak is their longest since August 2-10, 2003. Snow has reached double digits in five consecutive games, averaging 12 points in the stretch.
